amIReallyFree

public boolean amIReallyFree(java.lang.Void v,
                             Time s,
                             Time e,
                             java.util.BitSet timeSlot,
                             java.util.BitSet tSlot)
Returns true if nothing else is booked in the given time range. Sounds simple, and it is.

Specified by:
amIReallyFree in class GenAvail<java.lang.Void>
Parameters:
v - "Thing" to book. Since availability in this object is a very binary thing, this type doesn't matter much.
s - The start time
e - The end time
timeSlot - BitSet of all bits already booked between "s" and "e"
tSlot - BitSet containing the bit representation of "v" (0)
Returns:
!timeSlot.intersects(tSlot)

getBit

public int getBit(java.lang.Void v)
Returns the bit a given "Void" is to represent in the BitSet. As this object represents singular, binary availability (you're either available, or you aren't, w/o regard for anything else), this bit can be a single, constant value.

Specified by:
getBit in class GenAvail<java.lang.Void>
Parameters:
v - Nothing. Really, it's literally nothing.

0
